{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}} {{Infobox serial killer |name=Norman Afzal Simons |image= |image_size= |caption= |alias=The Station Strangler |birth_date={{birth date and age|df=yes|1967|1|12}} |birth_place=[[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]] |death_place= |cause= |victims=22 (1 conviction) |country=[[South Africa]] |states= |beginyear=1986 |endyear=1994 |apprehended=1994 |penalty=[[Life imprisonment]] (25 years for murder, 10 years for kidnap) }}
'''Norman Avzal Simons''' (born 12 January 1967), also known as the "'''Station Strangler,'''" is a [[South Africa]]n [[rape|rapist]] and [[serial killer]] who was convicted in 1995 of the rape and murder of 10-year-old Elroy van Rooy. He was sentenced to 35 years (25 for murder and 10 for kidnapping) in prison.<ref name="sstrangler">{{cite news|last1=Bailey|first1=Candice|title=Revisiting the Station Strangler cases|url=http://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/revisiting-the-station-strangler-cases-1.250970|accessdate=16 December 2015|publisher=[[Independent Online (South Africa)|IOL]]|date=16 August 2005}}</ref>
== Biography ==
Simons was an intelligent individual who enjoyed playing classical music and was capable of speaking seven languages including English, [[Afrikaans]], [[Xhosa people|Xhosa]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name="teacher">[http://www.crimezzz.net/serialkillers/S/SIMONS_norman_afzal.php. Serial Killer Crime Index.]</ref> He was employed as a Grade Five teacher at Alpine Primary School in Beacon Valley, [[Mitchell's Plain]].<ref name=sstrangler /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Whitaker|first1=Raymond|title=Coloured teacher charged in 'Cape Strangler' murder|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/coloured-teacher-charged-in-cape-strangler-murder-1371008.html|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=[[The Independent]]|date=19 April 1994}}</ref> Simons' victims were all young boys aged between 9 and 13.<ref name="victims">{{Cite web |url=http://news.iafrica.com/features/827627.htm |title=iAfrica : ''Worst Criminals of South Africa.'' |access-date=6 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612141639/http://news.iafrica.com/features/827627.htm |archive-date=12 June 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Simons and his victims were from the [[Cape Malays|Cape Malay]] community.<ref>{{cite news|title=Is Man Who Killed Boy S. Africa's Serial Strangler?|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/422660/IS-MAN-WHO-KILLED-BOY-S-AFRICAS-SERIAL-STRANGLER.html?pg=all|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=[[Deseret News]]|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=14 June 1995}}</ref>
Simons is believed to have started his sporadic series of murders in 29 October 1986,<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/station-strangler-up-for-parole-1687793 ''Station Strangler up for Parole'']</ref> ending only with his arrest nine years later in April 1994.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suspect held in 21 killings|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19940711&id=ZTQdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jaUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2361,3122136&hl=en|accessdate=16 December 2015|work=[[The Tuscaloosa News]]|date=11 July 1994}}</ref> He collected his moniker after it became apparent that most of his victims were lured away from train stations (Soviet serial killer [[Andrei Chikatilo]] had a similar ''modus operandi'').
Simons raped and sodomised his victims before strangling them. Victims were found face down with their hands tied behind their backs, buried in shallow sandy graves. In some cases the victims were found with their underwear around their necks, presumably used as a garrote. Hand-written notes were also found next to some victims.<ref name="victims"/> Simons' relationship with his older stepbrother seems to have a major bearing on his criminal activities. Simons alleges that his older stepbrother raped and sodomised him as a child. He also reports 'hearing voices' from his brother instructing him to kill. Simons' brother, an alcoholic, was murdered in 1991.
Simons appeared before magistrates in 1995 on one charge of murder and kidnap. His trial lasted three months, leading to a conviction and life sentence. He is currently serving his sentence in [[Drakenstein Correctional Centre|Drakenstein Maximum Correctional Facility]], [[Paarl]]. Simons appealed against his conviction in 1998, but his conviction was upheld.{{citation needed|date=December 2011}}
In 2005, an inquest was opened into the deaths of the remaining victims. After three years of further analysis, the victims' parents came no closer to an answer. On 9 December 2008, Regional Magistrate Marelize Rolle stated that she believed ''prima facie'' evidence showed Simons was probably responsible for the deaths of at least six of the other victims. However, due to the amount of time that had passed, she ruled out further prosecutions in the case.<ref name="prosecution">[http://allafrica.com/stories/200812100149.html Cape Argus : ''No further prosecutions for Simons.'']</ref>
Norman Simons converted to Islam in 1993, taking on the name Avzal, but converted back to Christianity in 1994.<ref name="Name">Pistorious, M. 2005. ''Profiling Serial Killers and other crimes in South Africa''. Penguin Books, South Africa. page 170. {{ISBN|0-14-302482-5}}</ref>
